## Fall Prevention Fundamentals

Falls from height remain one of the leading causes of serious injury in industrial and construction workplaces. Understanding when controls are required — and which controls to apply — is the first line of defence.

/assets/fall-hazard-zones.png
alt: Diagram of a warehouse showing fall hazard zones at elevated platforms and open floor edges
caption: Common fall hazard zones in a typical warehouse

### When is fall protection required?

Fall protection is required whenever work takes place at or above **1.5 metres** (5 feet) from a lower level, or at any height over open machinery, water, or other hazardous surfaces. This applies to walking surfaces, platforms, scaffolding, rooftops, and floor openings.

> The 1.5-metre threshold is a minimum. Many sites set a lower trigger. Always follow the more protective standard.
as: note
color: accent
style: outline

### Three levels of fall control

Use the hierarchy of controls to choose the most effective protection:

1. **Elimination** — redesign the task so work at height is not required.
2. **Passive protection** — guardrails, safety nets, covers over openings.
3. **Active protection** — personal fall arrest systems (PFAS) with harness, lanyard, and anchor point.

Passive protection is always preferred over active protection because it works without any action from the worker.

--

### Quick Check: Fall Protection Threshold

### At what height is fall protection required for standard platforms?
as: choice
points: 2
required: true

( ) 2.5 metres
feedback: 2.5 metres is above the threshold. Protection is required earlier than this.
( ) 3 metres
feedback: The requirement applies well below 3 metres.
(x) 1.5 metres
feedback: Correct. The standard threshold is 1.5 metres for most work surfaces.
( ) Only on rooftops
feedback: Fall protection applies to any elevated work surface, not only rooftops.

correct: Correct. The 1.5-metre threshold is the baseline requirement — always check your site standard, which may be more stringent.
incorrect: The standard threshold is 1.5 metres above a lower level. Review the regulations for your jurisdiction before proceeding.

