## Personal Fall Arrest Systems

A personal fall arrest system (PFAS) has three components that must all be present and correctly connected before work begins.

### The three components

### Anchorage
as: sequence
variant: numbered

The fixed attachment point — rated to hold a minimum of 22 kN (5,000 lbs) per attached worker. Select an anchor above the work position whenever possible to reduce free-fall distance.

### Body harness

A full-body harness distributes arrest forces across the thighs, pelvis, chest, and shoulders. Shoulder straps and leg loops must be snug but not restrictive. The dorsal D-ring is the only correct connection point for a fall arrest lanyard.

### Connecting subsystem

The lanyard, self-retracting lifeline (SRL), or energy absorber that connects the harness to the anchor. Maximum allowable free-fall is 1.8 metres. Always calculate total fall clearance — harness height, lanyard extension, deceleration distance, and safety margin — before beginning work.

--

### Inspect before use

Inspect every PFAS component at the start of each shift. Remove any component from service if you find:

- Cuts, abrasions, or burns on webbing or stitching
- Corrosion, cracks, or deformation on hardware
- Missing or illegible labels
- A deployed energy absorber (the system has been in a fall and must be retired)

> A PFAS that has arrested a fall must be immediately removed from service, even if it shows no visible damage.
as: note
color: warning
style: filled

--

### Quick Check: PFAS Components

### Select all three required components of a personal fall arrest system.
as: choice
points: 3
shuffle: true

[x] Anchorage point
feedback: Correct. The anchor is the fixed connection to structure.
[x] Full-body harness
feedback: Correct. The harness distributes arrest forces across the body.
[ ] Hard hat
feedback: A hard hat is required PPE but is not a component of the fall arrest system itself.
[x] Connecting subsystem (lanyard or SRL)
feedback: Correct. The connecting subsystem links harness to anchor and controls free-fall distance.
[ ] Safety glasses
feedback: Eye protection is separate PPE, not a fall arrest component.

---

## Summary and Reflection

Fall protection requires both the right equipment and the right decisions. The regulations set a floor — but professional judgment and site conditions often demand more.

### Key takeaways

- Fall protection is required at 1.5 metres or above any hazardous surface.
- Choose passive protection (guardrails, covers) over active protection (PFAS) wherever possible.
- A PFAS has three components: anchorage, harness, and connecting subsystem. All three must be inspected before each use.
- A deployed energy absorber means the system has been in a fall — retire it immediately.

--

### Reflection: Your worksite

### Describe one fall hazard on your worksite and the control currently in place.
as: free-response
required: true
attempts: 1

Include the location, the hazard type (e.g. open edge, ladder work, elevated platform), and whether the current control is passive or active. If you believe the control is inadequate, note what you would recommend instead.
